    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Partnership With China</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steve Kesten letter on Jiemian Yang's Mar 21 article opposes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Partnership Worth Preserving,'' by Jiemian Yang (Op-Ed, March 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Partnership Worth Preserving,'' by Jiemian Yang (Op-Ed, March 21):</p>
        <p>Preserving a partnership with a nation that espouses political policies as repressive as those we witnessed at Tiananmen Square, with a government that incarcerates political opponents in mental hospitals, a system that accepts the use of torture to obtain confessions, a bureaucracy that sends tens of thousands of its citizens to labor camps for ''re-education'' without judicial review -- all this flies in the face of the United States' traditional concern for international human rights standards.</p>
        <p>To promote an economic and political partnership with a nation that so persistently violates these basic rights without first addressing human rights reform signals the world that the moral fiber of our country is in serious need of attention.</p>
        <p>STEVE KESTEN  Alford, Mass., March 22, 2001</p>
      </block>
